{
  "Disease Name": "Contact Dermatitis (likely urushiol-induced from Poison Ivy or similar plant)",
  "Symptom Description": "Red, inflamed, and possibly blistering skin on the ear and adjacent scalp, consistent with an allergic reaction following contact with an irritant such as poison ivy.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Apply over-the-counter calamine lotion or hydrocortisone cream to relieve itching and inflammation. Take oatmeal baths or use baking soda soaks for soothing relief. Avoid scratching to prevent infection. If symptoms worsen or persist, consult a dermatologist for possible prescription-strength topical steroids or oral antihistamines."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Actinic Keratosis",
  "Symptom Description": "The lesion appears as a red, scaly, and slightly raised patch on sun-exposed skin, consistent with actinic keratosis. It may have a rough texture and show signs of inflammation or crusting.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Given the clinical appearance suggestive of actinic keratosis, a biopsy is recommended to rule out invasive squamous cell carcinoma, especially if the lesion is thick, bleeding, or atypical. If confirmed as actinic keratosis, treatment options include topical 5-fluorouracil or imiquimod cream applied daily over several weeks, photodynamic therapy for field cancerization, or cryotherapy. Regular follow-up and sun protection are essential to prevent progression and recurrence."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Not Applicable",
  "Symptom Description": "The image shows skin near the eyebrow and forehead with no visible signs of nail disease or fungal infection. There are minor redness and slight irritation, but no nail involvement.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "This image does not depict nail fungus or any nail-related condition. It appears to show normal skin with minor irritation. No antifungal treatment is indicated. If irritation persists, consult a dermatologist for evaluation of possible contact dermatitis or other skin conditions."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Seborrheic Keratosis",
  "Symptom Description": "Multiple brown to black, waxy, raised lesions with a stuck-on appearance on the skin, commonly seen in older individuals.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Electrodesiccation and curettage or cryotherapy can be used for removal if lesions are irritated, bleeding, or for cosmetic reasons. These methods typically result in minimal scarring when performed correctly."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Seborrheic Keratosis",
  "Symptom Description": "The lesion appears as a raised, waxy, or scaly growth with a stuck-on appearance, often brown or tan in color, located on the skin near the lip area. It may have a rough texture and sometimes exhibits minor crusting or scaling.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "For symptomatic relief or cosmetic purposes, treatment options include electrodesiccation and curettage or cryotherapy. These methods are effective for removal with minimal scarring when performed correctly. No treatment is necessary if the lesion is asymptomatic and benign."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Vasculitis",
  "Symptom Description": "The patient presents with skin ulcers and surrounding erythema, consistent with cutaneous vasculitis. The lesions appear as crusted, eroded areas with inflamed borders, suggesting vascular inflammation and tissue damage.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "A comprehensive evaluation is required to determine the underlying cause (primary vs. secondary vasculitis). Treatment may include systemic corticosteroids (e.g., prednisone) for inflammation control, immunosuppressants (e.g., cyclophosphamide or methotrexate) for severe cases, and wound care for ulcer management. If infection or drug-induced vasculitis is suspected, appropriate antimicrobial therapy or discontinuation of offending agents should be considered. Referral to a rheumatologist or dermatologist for further diagnostic workup (e.g., biopsy, serologic testing) is recommended."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Contact Dermatitis (likely urushiol-induced from Poison Ivy or similar plant)",
  "Symptom Description": "The patient exhibits bilateral, well-demarcated, erythematous, and crusted lesions on the lower legs, consistent with an allergic contact dermatitis. The lesions show signs of blistering and weeping, indicative of acute inflammation following exposure to an allergen such as urushiol from poison ivy.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Apply cool compresses using Burow's solution or oatmeal baths to soothe itching and reduce inflammation. Use over-the-counter hydrocortisone cream or calamine lotion for localized relief. Avoid scratching to prevent secondary infection. If symptoms are severe or widespread, consider oral antihistamines or a short course of systemic corticosteroids under medical supervision. Ensure thorough washing with soap and water within 2–8 hours after suspected exposure to remove residual urushiol."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Melanoma Skin Cancer",
  "Symptom Description": "A pink, raised lesion on the ear with irregular borders and possible surface scaling, suggestive of a suspicious mole that may be undergoing malignant transformation.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Surgical excision of the lesion with appropriate margins is recommended. If the lesion is confirmed as melanoma, sentinel lymph node biopsy may be indicated depending on thickness. Adjuvant therapy such as imiquimod cream postoperatively may be considered in select cases. Regular follow-up and skin surveillance are essential to monitor for recurrence or new lesions."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Exanthems and Drug Eruptions",
  "Symptom Description": "The patient presents with a widespread rash eruption on the lower abdominal and genital region, which may be associated with constitutional symptoms such as fever or fatigue. The rash is likely a reaction to an external trigger such as a drug, virus, or other allergen.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Discontinue any recently introduced medications that may be causing the eruption. Monitor for systemic symptoms and consider antihistamines or topical corticosteroids for symptomatic relief. If severe, seek immediate medical evaluation to rule out complex drug eruptions involving organ systems."
}

{
  "Disease Name": "Bullous Disease",
  "Symptom Description": "The skin shows multiple small red papules and vesicles scattered across a hairy area, with some areas showing slight erythema and possible early blister formation. No large bullae are clearly visible in this image.",
  "Treatment Plan Recommendation": "Given the appearance of vesiculobullous lesions, further diagnostic evaluation (e.g., biopsy, direct immunofluorescence) is recommended to determine if this is an immunobullous disease (e.g., pemphigoid, dermatitis herpetiformis) or infectious cause (e.g., herpes simplex, varicella-zoster). Treatment may include topical or systemic corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, or antiviral agents depending on the confirmed diagnosis. Avoid trauma to affected areas and maintain skin hygiene."
}
